    "Question 1: Build a Library Management System\n",
    "\n",
    "You are tasked with creating a class Book that represents a book in a library.\n",
    "Your class should make use of properties and dunder/magic methods to handle and manipulate book data.\n",
    "\n",
    "Requirements:\n",
    "\n",
    "    Attributes:\n",
    "        - title (string): The title of the book.\n",
    "        - author (string): The author of the book.\n",
    "        - stock (integer): The number of copies available in the library (must be a non-negative integer).\n",
    "    Properties:\n",
    "        - Create a property for stock that ensures the value is always a non-negative integer.\n",
    "          If someone tries to set a negative stock, raise a ValueError (\"raise ValueError\").\n",
    "\n",
    "    Dunder/Magic Methods:\n",
    "        - Implement the __str__ method to return a nicely formatted string with information about all attributes.\n",
    "        - Implement the __eq__ method to compare two books based on their title and author.\n",
    "        - Implement the __add__ method to allow adding two books' stocks together (e.g., book1 + book2 should return the total stock).\n",
    "\n",
    "    Additional Methods:\n",
    "        - Add a method sell_book(quantity) that reduces the stock by the specified quantity (use the stock property!).\n",
    "\n",
    "Now create 3 different book objects: \n",
    "book1 and book2, which have the exact same author and title but different stock.\n",
    "book3, which is something different.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, perform the following (make use of the dunder/magic methods!):\n",
    "    - Print all objects\n",
    "    - For all possible pairs of books, compare if they are the same, only if so, print the total stock.\n",
    "    - Pick any book and perform two different sell calls. The first one should be within the limit of available stock.\n",
    "      The second one should exceed that limit, so your stock property raises an Error.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
