    "Question 2: Numpy/Image operations\n",
    "\n",
    "You are given an image of sweet pepper plants in a glasshouse for further processing.\n",
    "For each of the tasks 2.1 and 2.2 create its own class!\n",
    "The constructors (__init__) of those classes should load the image, so you need to pass the image paths at object creation time.\n",
    "The actual act of processing however should be performed using a special dunder call (__call__) method, which is executed by calling the created object.\n",
    "This call should take the parameters necessary for the operation your class is meant to perform (either crop or segment) as arguments (i.e., x/y positions for cropping or channel thresholds for segmentation).\n",
    "The rest of this __call__ method should be designed to perform the tasks as described below.\n",
    "NOTE: When saving images, your output filenames need to be constructed using the original filename and the parameter values used at input when calling your object (not hardcoded!).\n",
    "\n",
    "2.1) Your first task is to load the given image into a numpy array and crop it somewhat nicely around the two red peppers.\n",
    "     You'll have to play around with the values a bit, to find what works. Save the cropped image to a file.\n",
    "\n",
    "2.2) - Load the saved image again into a numpy array. You now need to perform semantic segmentation of the red peppers,\n",
    "       by playing around with some threshold values for at least two of the three channels.\n",
    "       HINT: You should start using only the red channel, use a high value and lower it close to the point where parts of the pepper\n",
    "             will start to disappear. Then continue with green and/or blue and try to make some of the background noise disappear.\n",
    "             Your result does not need to be perfect! There will most probably be some leftover background noise and/or holes in the pepper.\n",
    "     - Save the result as both a binary mask, as well as a masked image (background black, valid pixels original values).\n",
    "       \n"
   ]
